# Using `.slice()`

Sometimes you need to rip a chunk of text right out of the middle of a string. We use the **`.slice()`** method.

You pass it two numbers: the **start index** (where to cut), and the **end index** (where to stop cutting).

```javascript
let fruits = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";

// Cut starting at Index 7, Stop cutting at Index 13
let myFruit = fruits.slice(7, 13);

console.log(myFruit); // Outputs "Banana"
```

## Leaving Off The End

If you only provide the **start index** to `.slice()`, it will automatically cut from that point all the way to the absolute end of the string!

```javascript
let fileName = "document.pdf";

// We just want the extension!
let extension = fileName.slice(8);

console.log(extension); // ".pdf"
```

It chopped off the first 8 characters, and kept everything else!

## Using `.replace()`

What if you want to find a specific word and swap it for another?

We use **`.replace()`**. You hand it two arguments: the 'target' string, and the 'replacement' string.

```javascript
let text = "I hate coding!";

// Let's fix that attitude.
let correctText = text.replace("hate", "love");

console.log(correctText); // "I love coding!"
```

*Note: Standard `.replace()` only replaces the FIRST match it finds, not all of them!*

